{"id":"1812.08833","submitter":"Stijn De Baerdemacker","authors":"Alexis De Vos and Stijn De Baerdemacker","title":"The Birkhoff theorem for unitary matrices of prime-power dimension","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The unitary Birkhoff theorem states that any unitary matrix with all row sums\nand all column sums equal unity can be decomposed as a weighted sum of\npermutation matrices, such that both the sum of the weights and the sum of the\nsquared moduli of the weights are equal to unity. If the dimension~$n$ of the\nunitary matrix equals a power of a prime $p$, i.e.\\ if $n=p^w$, then the\nBirkhoff decomposition does not need all $n!$ possible permutation matrices, as\nthe epicirculant permutation matrices suffice. This group of permutation\nmatrices is isomorphic to the general affine group GA($w,p$) of order only\n$p^w(p^w-1)(p^w-p)...(p^w-p^{w-1}) \\ll \\left( p^w \\right)!$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Dec 2018 20:37:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-24"}
