06}$Pb reaction. This fact has been\ncaused by the difference between the $N/Z$-ratios in the light fragments of the\nDNS formed during the capture in these reactions. The $N/Z$-ratio has been\nfound by solution of the transport master equations for the proton and neutron\ndistributions between fragments of the DNS formed at capture with the different\ninitial neutron numbers $N=18$ and $N=20$ for the reactions with the $^{34}$S\nand $^{36}$S, respectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Dec 2018 01:27:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-27"}
{"id":"1812.08907","submitter":"Sadjad Arzash","authors":"Sadjad Arzash, Jordan L. Shivers, Albert J. Licup, Abhinav Sharma,\n  Fred C. MacKintosh","title":"Stress-stabilized sub-isostatic fiber networks in a rope-like limit","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 99, 042412 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.99.042412","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The mechanics of disordered fibrous networks such as those that make up the\nextracellular matrix are strongly dependent on the local connectivity or\ncoordination number. For biopolymer networks this coordination number is\ntypically between three and four. Such networks are sub-isostatic and linearly\nunstable to deformation with only central force interactions, but exhibit a\nmechanical phase transition between floppy and rigid states under strain.\nIntroducing weak bending interactions stabilizes these networks and suppresses\nthe critical signatures of this transition. We show that applying external\nstress can also stabilize sub-isostatic networks with only tensile central\nforce interactions, i.e., a rope-like potential. Moreover, we find that the\nlinear shear modulus shows a power law scaling with the external normal stress,\nwith a non-mean-field exponent. For networks with finite bending rigidity, we\nfind that the critical stain shifts to lower values under prestress.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Dec 2018 01:44:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 3 Jan 2019 22:11:04 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 14 Mar 2019 20:18:15 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 3 Apr 2019 15:07:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-01"}
